# STRICT CORE PROJECT RULES

## 🛡️ Stability & Safety (NON-NEGOTIABLE)
- Never introduce any breaking change to public APIs under any circumstance unless explicitly requested.
- Never modify, delete, or alter existing behavior unless the task explicitly and directly requires it.
- Backward compatibility must be preserved in all changes, without exception.
- Any potential behavioral change must be treated as a risk and avoided by default.

## 🧱 Architecture (HARD CONSTRAINTS)
- Strictly respect existing architectural layers (API / service / data / domain).
- Never bypass, duplicate, or collapse established abstractions.
- Do not introduce new architectural patterns or redesigns.
- All new code MUST conform to existing module structure and dependency flow.

## 🧪 Code Quality (ENFORCED)
- Do not introduce code that breaks tests, linting, or type checks at any point.
- All changes must maintain full compatibility with existing test suite expectations.
- Dead code, unused imports, or partially used abstractions are strictly forbidden.
- Partial or “temporary” code is not allowed.

## 🔒 Scope Control (ZERO TOLERANCE FOR DRIFT)
- Implement ONLY what is explicitly requested in the task.
- Any change outside the minimal required scope is forbidden.
- No refactors, cleanup, renaming, or formatting changes unless explicitly requested.
- Do not modify files not strictly required for the task completion.

## 🎯 Consistency (STRICT ADHERENCE)
- Must follow existing project conventions exactly (naming, structure, error handling, patterns).
- Do not introduce alternative patterns, even if they seem “better” or more modern.
- Consistency with existing codebase overrides personal judgment or best-practice deviations.

## ⚠️ FINAL PRINCIPLE
- If a change feels like an improvement but was not explicitly requested → DO NOT DO IT.
